segments.text: And I always felt that it was extremely romantic.
What activities exactly were they both involved in in the community?
Well, my mother was a prominent artist in this area, and she belonged to the Women's Club, which she was always very proud of.
The Women's Club to her was an especially festive occasion, and it is the last thing she gave up.
once its vice president.
She was very active in church work, and so was my father.
She taught a Sunday school class and went to church every Sunday till long late in life.
And I remember quite distinctly her discussing the problem of going to church with one of my younger sons, who thought he didn't need to go to church.
And he said to her, he said, well, you don't go to church.
And she said, I have been.
That's great.
How many were in your family?
My mother and father had five children.
Are they living in this area, too?
Yes, two of my sisters, too, and my brother.
I've lost one brother, and the rest of them do live around here.
You told me your mother was involved in the women's club.
What exactly activities were they involved in?
Well, those ladies have spent their whole history in contributing to the cultural activities of the community.
The library for instance is their
They have, over the years, given us thousands and thousands of dollars to the library, and they continue to do so.
They have brought the best speakers and artists that they could to the club, paid them well, so that people in the community might have the privilege of listening to them.
You mentioned your mother was an artist.
drawings did she do?
She did everything.
Portraits and flowers and landscapes.
I often think that her, the best thing she did were flower portraits.
She did a blue bike picture which is as big as that wall over there.
My goodness.
I love it.
I own now.
And she, my father the night she died was
was telling how she painted and how—well, I remembered it's a—in the distance, you see this little country road, and in the distance you can see the church and the courthouse in Anderson, Texas.
Well, they sat on stools in that road, and she painted all day and however long it took her to do it.
That's great.
Did she do oil painting?
Yes, she painted in oil.
She painted all in watercolor with two mediums she used, and charcoal.
Were these available when she was younger and drawing, or when did she start this, when she was young?
I asked her once, and she said she could not remember when she was not drawing and painting.
That's great.
Do you draw yourself?
I couldn't draw a straight line if I had to, nor can I open a can.
Did she sell a number of these paintings over the years?
Yes, she did.
That's great.
There are a lot of her works, and she did a series of portraits of Texas heroes, and each of the schools named for one of those, that portrait is there.
And she did some pictures for various churches, Baptist churches, baptismal scenes.
Which do you feel is her most famous?
Was it this one with the blue bonnet?
Yes.
Everybody's always simply startled at that picture.
That's great.
What were your parents' names?
I don't believe I have their names.
My mother's name was Mary Martin Adams, and my father was George Ernest Adams.
Okay.
Okay.
And you are married too, is that correct?
Yes.
How did you meet your husband?
I met him during the war at A&M.
Was he a student here at A&M?
No, he was stationed here at that time.
I see.
Was there a military base here?
Yes, at A&M.
At A&M, I see.
Was it an Army base?
This particular branch that he belonged to was
Of course, we had everything here during the war, you know.
Oh, I didn't know that.
Yes, you did.
The Navy, the Air Force, they were all here.
Bryan Airfield was here.
That's right, that's right.
That was used, I guess, well, let's see, that was an Air Force field, or was that?
That property now belongs to Texas A&M University.
But it was previously an air base?
Air base.
Travis Bryan, Sr. was instrumental in getting it here.
I guess then a lot of the people in this area were affected by the war and I guess were called into service, is that correct?
Was your husband, I guess, did he go overseas too?
Yes.
What does your husband do now?
Oh, he's a university professor.
Oh, I didn't know that.
In which department?
In philosophy.
And I guess he enjoys this community as much as you do, right?
Well, he doesn't live here anymore.
Oh, I see.
Okay.
Let me see.
How did you, I guess you told me both of your parents, I guess especially your father was involved in a lot of political.
Yes, he was.
Involvements and things.
Served several terms in the Texas legislature.
He was mayor of Bryan twice.
He was on the school board a number of times.
I guess you're quite proud of him.
Yes.
I was amazed.
All my life I thought all this bit about public service, which my mother and father seemed to be so involved in, was a rather thankless
proposition, but I think people really appreciate them.
More people than ever came to anybody's funeral came to theirs.
And I'm still getting letters from people I never knew or heard of saying how much they appreciate what they have done for this community.
Were you active in
his campaigning for mayor here in the community?
No.
I wasn't in here.
I don't know where I was.
Oh, that's something.
When was he mayor here in Bryan?
I guess in the, I think in the 1950s.
Okay.
Do you know possibly what the
main issues were then, or the main problems in Bryan that, you know, he was, I'm sure had some ideas of things he wanted to change here, maybe, you know?
Well, he was always particularly interested in education, because he started out life as a school teacher.
And he always hoped that one of his children would be a school teacher, but none of them turned out to be.
I taught school for six months.
Oh my, that's something.
Did you teach in school after you graduated then, before you became a librarian?
That's great.
I taught in this little town out here called Iowa.
Iowa.
Which still exists.
Where is that located?
Well, it's out that way.
Okay.
When was that that you taught there?
It was in the early 1930s.
That's something.
What did you teach in elementary school?
Taught fifth grade.
That's great.
Did you feel at any time, or did you feel in the limelight when your dad was, when your father was mayor here, or did any of the children
Are your fellow friends envy you?
I don't think so.
You don't think so?
That's interesting.
What kind of—let's see, were there any particular
holidays or celebrations here in Bryan besides the traditional holidays that they celebrated during that year?
Any particular, did they have any like parades or fairs maybe?
Well they used to a long time ago have fairs every year.
Like a county fair?
Yes.
I don't believe they do anymore.
I can't remember the period of any time lately.
Right.
Did you ever go to them here?
Yes.
What were they like?
Do they show livestock?
Oh, lots of them.
They show livestock and things like that?
Yes.
What did Dad feel about you becoming a librarian?
Was he— Well, he was a gribble.
Gribble.
Yeah.
I taught my mother into talking into the assembly library school.
Everything went through her.
I see.
Did you do a lot of reading?
What stimulated you into becoming a librarian?
Was that part of it?
Yes.
Or did you spend yourself a lot of time in the library here?
Yes.
I spent all my time in the library here.
How did they work that with checking out books in those days?
Did they do it the same as they do now?

When they first began the library over there, you had a library card, and when you checked out a book, the library had a stamp, and she stamped your book, either the, I don't remember whether they stamped it the day you took it out, or the day you were to bring it back.
I think they stamped it the day you took it out, and then when they brought it back, they stamped it again.
I see.
And did you have a certain time you could keep the book out?
Yes.
I believe they both circulated for two weeks.
Now they circulate for three.
Three weeks.
How did you happen to get your position here at the library, your present position now?
Well, I was working in the Detroit Public Library at the time, and I looked at a professional journal.
I just casually saw that they were leaving the library in Bryan, so I applied for the job.
That's great.
And when was that, that you applied?
I guess it was in the 1960s.
I've been here fifteen years.
Fifteen years.
That's great.
And where were you before you were in Detroit?
Detroit Public.
Are these people here while you were away?
Yes.
Okay.
Did your brothers or sisters—did your brothers go to A&M here when they grew up and went to A&M?
Yes, they both.
What was their major field of interest there?
My older brother was an engineer.
He helped build the Alcon Highway in Alaska.
Oh, my.
I have a wonderful book with pictures of him and all the work that they did.
My younger brother went into agriculture.
When was this highway built?
During World War II.
During World War II?
That's great.
Did they ever regret not having women at the university?
Oh, no.
They thought the main deal was to have it all men.
To all men.
It remained for my niece, who was my brother's daughter, to make a test case.
Well...
My younger brother said that she ought to be put in a convent.
Oh, that's something.
What activities, did a lot of the boys go out of town to see their girlfriends during those times since there weren't girls here?
Yes, they did.
Every weekend they went to see their women.
So I guess the place kind of was deserted during that time?
T.W.U., which was called C.I.A.
then, you know.
What did that stand for?
College of Industrial Arts.
Oh, I see.
It's at Denton.
It's now called Texas University.
Right.
So a lot of them would go up there.
Did a lot of the fellows have cars during that time to take them around or to get to places, or?
Some of them did, but you know, now they all do.
Right.
What do you think has been your greatest satisfaction of living here in Bryan?
Being a librarian.
Being a librarian.
That's great.
Oh, when was it that your parents died?
Can you tell me that?
They've been dead, um, six years.
Six years.
Was your father in any other organizations, community organizations, before he became mayor, besides, you know, being involved so much with the university?
You know, I mean, like amends organizations here in Ryan, or do you know?
Well, he was a Rotarian.
He's very much devoted to that organization.
And what were their activities or are their activities?
They're a civic organization.
They're very powerful and influential in the community.
Do you think that, um, do you feel that people were more politically involved in, in their government, maybe here in Vine, or in the local area, than people are today, do you think?
No.
No?
No.
I think people are, in this area, are extremely interested in their government.
All right.
Uh, can you think of any of the
or maybe a problem in Bryan that was of particular interest to a lot of the people during your time that, you know, was maybe controversial or anything?
No, I suppose the greatest controversy in my time has been
a debate over whether the school board should be elected or appointed, and they finally decided to elect it.
For a long time, I believe it was the only such situation in the state of Texas.
So they were appointed?
They used to be appointed.
I see, I see.
What do you think is
has been your greatest joy as far as being a citizen here in Bryan?
Being the librarian.
Being the librarian.
That's great.
How long have you been the head librarian here?
Fifteen years.
Fifteen years.
That's great.
Were you a librarian in Detroit before you came here?
Yes.
I don't think I've got any more questions.
